<POR_COPY_TXT><![CDATA[ This project deals with a connection between dyamical systems and  number theory. A  dynamical system here stands for an abstract set of  points together   with an evolution law which governs the way points  move over time. It   turns out that many problems concerning  simultaneous approximation of   real numbers by rational numbers can be  understood in terms of the   behavior of certain orbits. Furthermore,  systems that arise in this   context are of algebraic nature (so-called  homogeneous spaces), which makes it possible to use a wide   variety of  sophisticated tools for their investigation.  One  important theme of the project was studying exceptional trajectories  and corresponding number-theoretical objects. For example divergent trajectories on the space of lattices correspond to singular systems of linear forms. Jointly with Kadyrov,  Lindenstrauss and  Margulis the PI estimated the Hausdorff dimension of the set of singular systems from above. Singular vectors were found on any analytic nondegenerate submanifold of R^n in the joint work with Moshchevitin and Weiss. With Mirzadeh the PI obtained an estimate for the Hausdorff dimension of the set of points in a homogeneous space whose trajectories avoid a fixed subset. This also has number-theoretic applications.   Another direction was related to rational points on quadric hypersurfaces, whose distribution was stidued using dynamics. Suppose that there is a dense set of those points. How are they distributed? and how likely is it to find a rational point with relatively small denominator not far from a typical point on the hypersurface? This was the subject of the PI's paper with  Fishman, Merrill and Simmons. The dynamical system responsible for the approximation properties happens to be a flow on a quotient of the special orthogonal group of the corresponding quadratic form.  Yet another direction is studying improvement of Dirichlet's theorem, which is related to the behavior of certain trajectories near critical loci in the space of lattices. A 0-1 law in one dimension and for inhomogeneous approximation was proved jointly with Wadleigh, and extenstions to arbitrary norm appeared in the paper with Rao.  Other results include: effective equidistribution of flows with a rate (joint with Shi and Weiss), and a dynamical Borel-Cantelli lemma for discrete-time flows on hyperbolic manifolds (with Zhao).       Last Modified: 09/30/2020       Submitted by: Dmitry Y Kleinbock]]></POR_COPY_TXT>
